\"$?\"\"$5#\"$_#F'F&F%F$F#" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "The " }
{TEXT 259 16 "Binomial Theorem" }{TEXT -1 66 " gives a formula for fin
ding the coefficients of the expansion of " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)^n;" 
"6#),&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&%\"nG" }{TEXT -1 10 "  for any " }{TEXT 267 1 
"n" }{TEXT -1 53 ".  It is relatively obvious that the coefficient of \+
 " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "a^(n-k)*b^k;" "6#*&)%\"aG,&%\"nG\"\"\"%\"kG!\"\"F()
%\"bGF)F(" }{TEXT -1 19 "  for any value of " }{TEXT 268 1 "k" }{TEXT 
-1 11 " from 0 to " }{TEXT 269 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 46 " is given by the nu
mber of ways we can choose " }{TEXT 270 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 8 " of the " }
{TEXT 294 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 12 "'s from the " }{TEXT 271 1 "n" }{TEXT 
-1 1 " " }{TEXT 295 1 "b" }{TEXT -1 20 "'s in the expansion " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)*(a+b)" "6#*&,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF&F&,&F%F&F'F&F&" }
{TEXT -1 7 " ....( " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "(a+b)" "6#,&%\"aG\"\"\"%\"bGF%" }
{TEXT -1 5 " ),  " }{TEXT 272 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 41 " times .   The numbe
r of combinations of " }{TEXT 273 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 18 " objects choosin
g " }{TEXT 274 1 "k" }{TEXT -1 12 " at a time, " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "nCk" 
"6#%$nCkG" }{TEXT -1 27 ", is given by the formula  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "
nCk=n!/(k!*(n-k)!)" "6#/%$nCkG*&-%*factorialG6#%\"nG\"\"\"*&-F'6#%\"kG
F*-F'6#,&F)F*F.!\"\"F*F2" }{TEXT -1 2 " ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 261 10 "State the " }{TEXT 260 16 "Binomi
al Theorem" }{TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 275 31 "and use Maple to demonstrat
e it" }{TEXT -1 1 "." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 297 344 "****The binomia
l theorem uses the fact that the coefficients of the terms of an expan
ded binomial raised to any power make a predictable pattern and gives \+
an equation for finding the coefficient of any term, if you know the p
ower that the binomial is raised to and the power of b in the term who
se coefficient you want to know.  To demonstrate:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT 298 3 "   " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "expand((
a+b)^4);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,,*$)%\"aG\"\"%\"\"\"F(*(F
'F()F&\"\"$F(%\"bGF(F(*(\"\"'F()F&\"\"#F()F,F0F(F(*(F'F(F&F()F,F+F(F(*
$)F,F'F(F(" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 89 "The binomial theore
m says that the coefficient of the second term will be 4!/1!(4-1)! = 4
" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 17 "(4!/(1!*(4-1)!));" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"\"%" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 8 "
Compute " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "sum(binomial(n,k),k=0..n)" "6#-%$sumG6$-%)bi
nomialG6$%\"nG%\"kG/F*;\"\"!F)" }{TEXT -1 34 "  for n=1 to 10.  Here t
he symbol " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "Sigma;" "6#%&SigmaG" }{TEXT -1 70 " (Greek
 letter Sigma) stands for sum.   (See the worksheet SumSeq.mws)" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 54 "for n from 1 to 10\ndo n,s
um(binomial(n,k),k=0..n);\nod;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"
\"\"\"#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"#\"\"%" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"$\"\")" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"
%\"#;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"&\"#K" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "
" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"'\"#k" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"(\"$
G\"" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\")\"$c#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"*\"$7&" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"#5\"%C5
" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 12 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
258 60 "What general formula do the above calculations in  suggest?\n
" }{TEXT 299 125 "****The general formula is that the sum of the coeff
icients of the n terms will be 2^n, where n is the power of the binomi
al." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 388 "2
.  Pascal's Triangle.  Recall the definition of Pascal's Triangle.   U
se Maple to construct the first 10 rows of Pascal's Triangle. (The tri
ck will be to get the coefficients to occur in the correct order.  The
 Maple command for generating a sequence might be helpful. It is   seq
(expression(i),i=m..n);   where expression(i) is an expression with in
dex i and m..n is a range of numbers." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 3 " \+
  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 56 "for j from 0 to 9\ndo \+
seq(coeff((a+1)^j,a,i),i=0..j);\nod;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "
6#\"\"\"" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$\"\"\"F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6%\"\"\"\"\"#F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6&\"
\"\"\"\"$F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6'\"\"\"\"\"%\"\"'F$F#
" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6(\"\"\"\"\"&\"#5F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 
"" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6)\"\"\"\"\"'\"#:\"#?F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6*\"\"\"\"\"(\"#@\"#NF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6+\"\"\"\"\")\"#G\"#c\"#qF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6,\"\"\"\"\"*\"#O\"#%)\"$E\"F'F&F%F$F#" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 214 "3.  Functions.  In thi
s exericse we study the basic properties of polynomials and rational f
unctions.  Some revelant MAPLE commands will be   factor, expand, solv
e, fsolve, denom, numer, simplify, subs,   ....... ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 171 "     The first thing we need to learn is how to define
 a function.  There are two ways, each with its own advantages and dis
advantages.  First define the polynomial p1 as " }{TEXT 282 2 "a " }
{TEXT -1 1 "s" }{TEXT 283 23 "ymbolic expression in x" }{TEXT -1 119 "
 in the following way:    p1:=x^2-1;  (Note the colon before the =, th
is is always required when defining something.)  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "p1:=x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6
#>%#p1G,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 "     Now define the same polynomial a
s " }{TEXT 281 30 "an operation on the variable x" }{TEXT -1 40 " in t
he following way:     p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "
" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p2Gf*6#%\"xG6\"6$%)operatorG%&arrowGF(,&*$)9$
\"\"#\"\"\"F1F1!\"\"F(F(F(" }}}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 257 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 190 "Try the following command sequences to
 see some of the differences in how MAPLE  treats these two definition
s.  As always record your observations and comments on the worksheet i
n text mode." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 
"" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "p1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)%\"xG\"
\"#\"\"\"F(F(!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "p2;" }
}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#%#p2G" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
77 "*****p1 prints the expression, p2 just prints the name of the oper
ation (p2)." }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "p2(x);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F(F(!\"\"" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 8 "p2(t-3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$),&%\"tG\"\"\"\"\"$!\"\"\"\"#F(F(F(F*" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "p2(u^3-u^2+2);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$),(*$)%\"uG\"\"$\"\"\"F+*$)F)\"\"#F+!\"\"F.F+F.F+F+
F+F/" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "    " }{TEXT 300 135 "******p2 (d
efining an operation) takes whatever value you put in and prints out t
hat value substitued for x in the original statement. " }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 255 "     This works just like we expect substitution to
 work because p2 is an operation on whatever is in the (  ).  However \+
since p1 is a symbolic expression we have some difficulties with subst
ituting into it directly.   Try the following command sequences." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
6 "p1(x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)-%\"xG6#F'\"\"#\"\"
\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 8 "p1(t-3);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)-%\"xG6#,&%\"tG\"\"\"\"\"$!\"\"\"
\"#F+F+F+F-" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "p1(u^3-u^2+2
);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*$)-%\"xG6#,(*$)%\"uG\"\"$\"\"
\"F.*$)F,\"\"#F.!\"\"F1F.F1F.F.F.F2" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 135 "      Notice the extra x in front.  Th
is is curious and not very reassuring.  To substitute into a symbolic \+
expression we must use the " }{TEXT 284 4 "subs" }{TEXT -1 9 " command
." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "subs(x=t-3,p1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#,&
*$),&%\"tG\"\"\"\"\"$!\"\"\"\"#F(F(F(F*" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "subs(x=6,p1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"#N
" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 6 "p2(6);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 
"" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"#N" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "    " }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 75 "     Now let's do some simple operations on thi
s polynomial.  In each case " }{TEXT 277 46 "Explain what the command \+
appears to have done." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 11 "factor(p1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {TEXT -1 
