\"\"*&%\"bGF&F(F&F*" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 2 "  " }{TEXT 279 58 "What's the famous formula we get when
 we solve p3=0 for x?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 34 "We get the quadr
atic equation!!!!!" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 169 "  See if MAPLE knows a general formula for solving gener
al cubic polynomials, i.e. is there a 3rd order formula comparable to \+
the quadratic formula?  If so, exhibit it. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 22 "p4:=a*x^3+b*x^2+c*
x+d;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p4G,**&%\"aG\"\"\")%\"xG\"
\"$F(F(*&%\"bGF()F*\"\"#F(F(*&%\"cGF(F*F(F(%\"dGF(" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 
"> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "solve(p4=0,x);" }}{PARA 12 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6%,(*(\"\"'!\"\"%\"aGF&,***\"#O\"\"\"%\"bGF+%\"cGF+F'F+F+
*(\"$3\"F+%\"dGF+)F'\"\"#F+F&*&\"\")F+)F,\"\"$F+F&**\"#7F+F6#F+F2,,*(
\"\"%F+F'F+)F-F6F+F+*&)F-F2F+)F,F2F+F&*,\"#=F+F,F+F-F+F'F+F0F+F&*(\"#F
F+)F0F2F+F1F+F+*(F<F+F0F+F5F+F+F9F'F+F+#F+F6F+*,F2F+F6F&,&*(F6F+F'F+F-
F+F+*$F@F+F&F+F'F&F(#F&F6F&*(F6F&F,F+F'F&F&,**(F8F&F'F&F(FGF&**F6F&FIF
+F'F&F(FLF+*(F6F&F,F+F'F&F&*(^#F9F+F6F9,&*(F%F&F'F&F(FGF+*,F2F+F6F&FIF
+F'F&F(FLF+F+F+,**(F8F&F'F&F(FGF&**F6F&FIF+F'F&F(FLF+*(F6F&F,F+F'F&F&*
(^##F&F2F+F6F9FTF+F+" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 280 170 "Why do you think high school stude
nts are never asked to remember the general formula for the roots of a
 cubic?\n*****It would be impossible, cruel and unusual punishment." }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 113 "4.  Sol
ving Equations in One Variable.   There are two different commands to \+
direct Maple to solve an equation:  " }{TEXT 285 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 
5 " and " }{TEXT 286 7 "fsolve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "They h
ave different purposes.  The " }{TEXT 287 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 63 " com
mand attempts to find exact solutions.  If the expression  " }{TEXT 
289 1 "f" }{TEXT -1 116 "  is defined in terms of only one variable, t
here are several different ways to direct Maple to solve the equation \+
 " }{TEXT 290 5 "f  = " }{TEXT 291 4 "0.  " }{TEXT -1 54 "The followin
g all cause Maple to solve the equation   " }{TEXT 292 5 "f  = " }
{TEXT 293 2 "0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 16 "       solve(f);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "       s
olve(f,x);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f=0);" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 20 "       solve(f=0,x);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 349 "Maple makes an assumptio
n that if the coefficients of a polynomial are all given exactly (as i
ntegers or rational numbers [ratios of integer]), then you are only in
terested in finding exact solutions.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algeb
ra doesn't guarantee that the solutions of  a polynomial can be found \+
exactly, only the polynomial has solutions.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 78 "You can force Maple to re
port additional (approximate) solutions by using the " }{TEXT 288 6 "f
solve" }{TEXT -1 75 " command.  (What does the \"f\" stand for?  f sta
nds for floating point.)  In" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "addition
, to forcing Maple to report approximate solutions, you can specify a \+
field extension (typically real or complex) and require Maple to look \+
for solutions which fit in that field extension.  Also, one can specif
y a range of x values and force" }{TEXT 296 7 " fsolve" }{TEXT -1 75 "
 to only look for solutions in that specified range.  For example, com
pare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "solve(4*x-x^3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%\"
\"!\"\"#!\"#" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "fsolve(4*x-
x^3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%$!+++++?!\"*$\"\"!F'$\"+++++?
F%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 23 "fsolve(4*x-x^3,x=1..4
);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"+++++?!\"*" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 115 "The first one solves for approximations of x. \+
 The second one asks for only the solutions that are between 1 and 4.
" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "For \+
each of the polynomials " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[1]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"\"\"" }
{TEXT -1 9 " through " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[14]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"#9" }{TEXT 
-1 19 ", do the following:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "     a.   s
olve for all exact roots whereever possible, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 59 "     b.   find all approximate roots to 10 decimal places
, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 43 "     c.  factor each into linear fa
ctors.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
106 "You will need to click on  [> in the toolbar to obtain new execut
ion lines just below the cursor position." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "p[1] := x^2-2;" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>&%\"pG6#\"\"\",&*$)%\"xG\"\"#F'F'F,!
\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 52 "solve(p[1],x);\nfso
lve(p[1],x);\nfactor(p[1],complex);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6
