{TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "5.  Solving Systems of E
quations in Several Variables.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 49 "When we have an equation in two variables
, e.g.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x -2*y = 5" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&
\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"\"&" }{TEXT -1 147 "  we often associate with it \+
a graph, the set of points (x,y) in the two-dimensional plane which sa
tisfy the equation.  For a linear equation like " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x-
2*y = 5" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"\"&" }
{TEXT -1 89 " the graph is a straight line.  For more a complicated eq
uation in two variables, e.g.,  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "2*x^3 -3*x + y^2 = x
*y" "6#/,(*&\"\"#\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"$F'F'*&F*F'F)F'!\"\"*$%\"yGF&F'*&F)F
'F.F'" }{TEXT -1 45 "  the graph becomes a more complicated curve." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 282 "When we \+
have two equations in two variables, we think of the solution set of t
his system of equations as being the set of points (x,y) which satisfy
 both equations simultaneously.  In terms of their graphs, the solutio
n set is the set of points where the graphs intersect (cross).  " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 622 "When we \+
have two linear equations in two variables, since their graphs are str
aight lines, then two straight lines, if they cross, will cross in exa
ctly one place.  Hence, the solution set of the system of equations wi
ll be exactly one point (x,y).  If we have two equations which are mor
e complicated, then the number of intersection points (crossing points
) of their graphs can vary.  For example, if the graph of one equation
 is a circle and the graph of the other equation is a straight line, t
hen, if their graphs cross, then number of solutions (intersection poi
nts) of the system of equations could be 1 or 2.  Etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 128 "We can instruct Map
le to find solutions of systems of equations using the solve or fsolve
 commands.  The syntax for doing so is:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 
"" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 30 "     solve( \{eq1,eq2\}, \{x,y\});" 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 85 "where \+
eq1 and eq2 are equations in the variables x and y.  This is illustrat
ed below." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 42 "solve(\{ x + 2*y = 5, 2*x-3*y = -1\},\{x,y\});" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"yG#\"#6\"\"(/%\"xG#\"#8F(" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 22 "We could \+
have defined " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 40 "eq1 := x + 2
*y = 5;\neq2 := 2*x-3*y = -1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%$eq
1G/,&%\"xG\"\"\"*&\"\"#F(%\"yGF(F(\"\"&" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
20 "6#>%$eq2G/,&*&\"\"#\"\"\"%\"xGF)F)*&\"\"$F)%\"yGF)!\"\"F." }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 26 "and then \+
given the command" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 25 "solve( \{eq1
,eq2\}, \{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"yG#\"#6\"\"
(/%\"xG#\"#8F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 55 "and achieved the same result.  Remember the solution  (" 
}{XPPEDIT 19 1 "13/7" "6#*&\"#8\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 2 ", " }
{XPPEDIT 19 1 "11/7" "6#*&\"#6\"\"\"\"\"(!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 166 ") repre
sents a point in the two-dimensional plane (why two-dimensional?  Beca
use there are only two variables!) where the graphs of the equations i
ntersect (cross).  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 63 "Find the solutions, if they exist, for the following eq
uations " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
4 "a.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*x - 2*y = 6" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&
\"\"#F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"\"'" }{TEXT -1 3 ",  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "4*x + y = \+
-2" "6#/,&*&\"\"%\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'%\"yGF',$\"\"#!\"\"" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 
"> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 34 "solve(\{3*x-2*y=6,4*x+y=-2\},\{x,y\});" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"xG#\"\"#\"#6/%\"yG#!#IF(" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "b.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "6*x -9*y = 12" "6#/,
&*&\"\"'\"\"\"%\"xGF'F'*&\"\"*F'%\"yGF'!\"\"\"#7" }{TEXT -1 3 ",  " }
{XPPEDIT 19 1 "3*y - 2*x = 3" "6#/,&*&\"\"$\"\"\"%\"yGF'F'*&\"\"#F'%\"
xGF'!\"\"F&" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 36 "solve(\{6*x-9
*y=12,3*y-2*x=3\},\{x,y\});" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 74 "li
nes have the same slope (2/3) and so are parallel--there is no solutio
n." }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "c.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "y = x - x^2" 
"6#/%\"yG,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$F&\"\"#!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 3 ",  " }{XPPEDIT 19 
1 "y = x-4" "6#/%\"yG,&%\"xG\"\"\"\"\"%!\"\"" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 
"" {MPLTEXT 1 0 29 "solve(\{y=x-x^2,y=x-4\},\{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6$<$/%\"yG!\"#/%\"xG\"\"#<$/F(F&/F%!\"'" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 100 "This one has two solutions.  One is a cu
rve and one is a straight line that crosses the curve twice." }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "d.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "x^2 + y^2 = 16" "6#/
,&*$%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"*$%\"yGF'F(\"#;" }{TEXT -1 3 ",  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 
"x^2/36 + y^2/4 = 1" "6#/,&*&%\"xG\"\"#\"#O!\"\"\"\"\"*&%\"yGF'\"\"%F)
F*F*" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 41 "solve(\{x^2+y^2=16,x
^2/36+y^2/4=1\},\{x,y\});" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"yG-
%'RootOfG6#,&\"\"&!\"\"*&\"\"#\"\"\")%#_ZGF-F.F./%\"xG,$*&\"\"$F.-F'6$
,&*&F-F.F/F.F.F5F+/%&labelG%%_L13GF.F." }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "evalf(%);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#<$/%\"xG$
\"+;YBuO!\"*/%\"yG$\"+I)Q6e\"F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "e.  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "x^2+y^2 = 16" "6#/,&
*$%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"*$%\"yGF'F(\"#;" }{TEXT -1 4 ",   " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "
x + y = 6" "6#/,&%\"xG\"\"\"%\"yGF&\"\"'" }{TEXT -1 4 "    " }}{EXCHG 
